data.content:
AWS
AWS is a major public cloud provider offering elastic compute, managed Kubernetes orchestration, and integrated storage and monitoring stacks.

Azure
Azure is a cloud service by Microsoft providing scalable infrastructure solutions including Kubernetes services.

Google Cloud
Google Cloud provides public cloud environments with elastic compute resources and managed Kubernetes orchestration.

EKS
EKS (Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service) is a managed service that makes it easy to run Kubernetes on AWS without needing to install and operate your own Kubernetes control plane.

AKS
Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS) simplifies deploying, managing, and operations of Kubernetes clusters in Azure.

GKE
Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE) provides a managed environment for deploying, managing, and scaling containerized applications using Google infrastructure.

NVIDIA A100
NVIDIA A100 is a GPU designed for data centers to accelerate AI workloads with high throughput and performance capabilities.

H100
H100 is another high-performance GPU by NVIDIA, suitable for demanding AI applications and on-premise deployment scenarios.

Terraform
An infrastructure as code tool that allows users to build, change, and version infrastructure safely and efficiently.<SEP>Terraform is an infrastructure as code tool that allows users to build, change, and version infrastructure safely and efficiently.

Pulumi
Pulumi is an infrastructure-as-code platform that uses general-purpose programming languages for defining cloud resources.

AWS Secrets Manager
A service provided by AWS to help you protect access to your applications, services, and IT resources without the upfront cost and complexity of managing your own infrastructure.

Azure Key Vault
A cloud service for securely storing and accessing secrets in Azure cloud environments.

NVIDIA Triton Inference Server
A server designed by NVIDIA to serve AI models at scale, supporting dynamic batching, GPU multiplexing, and multi-model deployment.

TensorFlow Serving
An open-source serving system for machine learning models, optimized for production environments.

TorchServe
A flexible and easy-to-use tool for serving PyTorch models at scale in production settings.

Kubernetes
An open-source platform for automating deployment, scaling, and operations of application containers across clusters of hosts.<SEP>Kubernetes is a platform where RBAC policies are applied to manage access control, enhance security, and configure infrastructure components within the context of deploying an AI system.

IAM roles
Identity and Access Management roles are used to define permissions for accessing AWS resources securely.

virtual networks
Virtual networks are isolated network environments within cloud infrastructure used for secure communication between services.

storage classes
Storage classes in Kubernetes define storage policies, such as performance and replication, on persistent volumes.

CRI-O
A lightweight container runtime for Kubernetes, which implements the Kubernetes Container Runtime Interface (CRI).

kubeadm
A tool provided by Kubernetes to bootstrap a minimum viable cluster that conforms to best practices.

Rancher
An open-source platform for managing containers and Kubernetes clusters at scale.

NVMe-based storage
A high-performance storage protocol designed for use with solid-state drives in data centers.

LVM
Logical Volume Manager, a device mapper that provides logical volume management for the Linux kernel.

RAID strategies
Redundant Array of Independent Disks is used to combine multiple disk drive components into a single logical unit.

firewall zoning
A security practice that divides networks into zones for enhanced access control and threat mitigation.

VPN tunneling
Secures data transmission over public or untrusted networks by creating encrypted connections between devices.

Istio Gateway
A service mesh component that manages traffic flow across services, including security and monitoring.

Envoy Proxy
An open-source edge/middleware proxy designed for cloud-native applications.

OAuth2
An authorization framework enabling applications to obtain limited access to user accounts on HTTP services.

JWT (JSON Web Token)
A compact, URL-safe means of representing claims to be transferred between two parties.

Kafka
An open-source stream-processing software platform developed by LinkedIn and donated to the Apache Software Foundation.

RabbitMQ
A message broker that implements the Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP).

Redis
An in-memory data structure store, used as a database, cache, and message broker.

Memcached
A distributed memory caching system that speeds up dynamic web applications by alleviating database load.

PostgreSQL
An open-source relational database management system emphasizing extensibility and SQL compliance.

Amazon S3
A scalable object storage service provided by Amazon Web Services (AWS).

Azure Blob Storage
An object/blob storage solution offered by Microsoft Azure for large amounts of unstructured data.

Fluent Bit
A lightweight log processor and forwarder for cloud-native environments.

Fluentd
An open-source data collector designed to unify logging layers.

Elasticsearch
A distributed, RESTful search and analytics engine capable of addressing a growing number of use cases.

Loki
A horizontally-scalable, highly-available, multi-tenant log aggregation system inspired by Prometheus.

OpenTelemetry
An observability framework for cloud-native software, providing APIs and libraries to collect telemetry data.

Grafana
A platform for monitoring and observability that allows users to create, explore, and share dashboards featuring live data.

Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA)
Automatically scales the number of pods in a replication controller, deployment, or replica set based on observed CPU utilization.

KEDA
The Kubernetes-based Event Driven Autoscaling system that allows for event-driven autoscaling of workloads.

node selectors
A Kubernetes concept used to constrain which nodes your pod is eligible to be scheduled on based on labels.

tolerations
Tolerations are applied to pods, and allow (but do not require) the pods to schedule onto nodes with matching taints.

affinity rules
Defines rules that constrain which nodes a pod is eligible to be scheduled on based on labels.

readiness probes
A mechanism in Kubernetes for checking the readiness of a container to accept traffic before it starts receiving requests.

liveness probes
Used by Kubernetes to know when to restart a container.

HashiCorp Vault
A tool for managing secrets and protecting sensitive data, provided by HashiCorp.<SEP>HashiCorp Vault is a tool mentioned for managing secrets securely within the system's architecture.

Slack
Slack is mentioned as a communication channel used in observability components to monitor AI systems.

PagerDuty
PagerDuty is referred to as a tool for monitoring system behavior and notifications related to AI systems.

Opsgenie
Opsgenie is used in conjunction with other tools like Slack and PagerDuty for effective observability of AI systems.

RBAC (Role-Based Access Control)
RBAC is a method used in Kubernetes for restricting access to APIs, secrets, and logs, ensuring that only authorized entities can perform certain operations.

mTLS (Mutual Transport Layer Security)
mTLS is enforced between services to prevent eavesdropping and service spoofing as part of security measures.

Ingress Controllers
Ingress controllers are used to filter inbound IPs and limit request rates, contributing to secure API access management in Kubernetes environments.

Sealed Secrets
Sealed Secrets are used as part of the toolkit to manage and protect sensitive data by encrypting secrets before storing them in version control systems.

Artillery
Artillery is a tool utilized for simulating user demand during the final validation process of an AI system, helping reveal performance boundaries.

Locust
Locust is mentioned as a stress testing tool used to simulate user demand and evaluate the resilience and behavior of the AI system under test conditions.

k6
k6 is employed for stress testing to verify system performance and ensure that autoscaling logic functions correctly under simulated load.

AppArmor
AppArmor is a security module for Linux that restricts programs' capabilities with per-program profiles.

SELinux (Security-Enhanced Linux)
SELinux is a set of kernel modifications and user-space tools designed to provide fine-grained access control policies, enhancing system security by restricting processes.

DLP Scanners (Data Loss Prevention)
DLP scanners are used to monitor and protect data from being exfiltrated through unauthorized channels by detecting potential breaches or leaks.

Autoscaling Logic
Autoscaling logic refers to the mechanisms and rules that automatically adjust resources in response to system load, ensuring optimal performance and resource utilization.

Trace Analysis
End-to-end trace analysis involves examining the entire workflow of a process or transaction across different components to identify bottlenecks and inefficiencies.
